Loading California and Avocado Data

  • The data, which represents âMedian sales price of existing single family homes in California in March 2021 and March 2022, by countyâ was pulled from https://www.statista.com/statistics/1268547/sales-price-of-existing-single-family-homes-in-california/.
Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(readxl)
avocados <- read_csv(here("data", "avocado.csv"))
cali_housing <- read_xlsx(here("data", "California Housing Prices.xlsx"),
                          sheet = "Data",
                          skip = 4) |> 
  rename("region" = "...1",
         "March2021" = "Mar '21",
         "March2022" = "Mar '22")
  
#California regions
california_regions <- tibble(CaliforniaRegions = c("San Francisco", "San Diego", "Los Angeles",
                             "Sacramento"))

region_prices_cali <- cali_housing |> 
  semi_join(california_regions, by = c("region" = "CaliforniaRegions"))

#Removing spaces to match Avocado dataset format
region_prices_cali$region[region_prices_cali$region == "San Francisco"] <- "SanFrancisco"
region_prices_cali$region[region_prices_cali$region == "San Diego"] <- "SanDiego"
region_prices_cali$region[region_prices_cali$region == "Los Angeles"] <- "LosAngeles"
Code 
#Merging with Avocados
housing_avocados_cali <- avocados |> 
  inner_join(region_prices_cali, by = "region") |> 
  select(AveragePrice, `Total Volume`, region, March2022) |> 
  mutate(March2022 = as.factor(March2022))
Code 
options(scipen = 999)

#Finding Correlations
housing_avocados_cali |> 
  group_by(region, March2022) |> 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = region, y = AveragePrice, fill = March2022)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "California Regions", 
       y = "Average Avocado Price (In Dollars)", 
       fill = "Median Housing Price")

Code 
housing_avocados_cali |> 
  group_by(region, March2022) |> 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = region, y = `Total Volume`, color = March2022)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.15, size = 1) +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "",
       title = "Total Avocados Purchased per California Region", 
       color = "Median Housing Price \nper Region")

There looks to be an increasing trend in the average price of avocados as the median housing price increases, but Sacramento does not coincide with this trend. If we neglect to look at Sacramentoâs data, itâs evident in the box plot that there is some significant positive correlation between median housing and average avocado price.

When it comes to total avocado sales volume by region, Los Angeles consumes almost five times as many avocados as San Francisco, which has the second highest total avocado sales volume. But Los Angeles has an extremely high population, so itâs best to just look at the first plot.

Using our first graph to address the claim âMillennials canât afford houses, because they spend all their money buying avocado toastâ, brings us to the conclusion that as Millennials move to more expensive areas, average avocado prices will likely be higher. Therefore, they should reduce avocado toast consumption to help save some extra cash to afford their more expensive home. But average avocado price doesnât vary much relative to the drastic differences in median housing prices, so Millennials have much more to worry about when saving money than their obsession with avocado toast. In conclusion, Millennials arenât able to afford homes due to avocado toast consumption, but rather the insanely high median housing prices in California.

The main focus here is where in California we are, so putting housing price as an annotation makes that clear.

When I used the bar-plot originally for median housing price and total avocados purchased, I had forgotten that the total avocados purchased data hadnât been summarized into one number like median housing price had. If I remember correctly, I figured I would use a box-plot instead, but due to all the small total purchase values I thought it looked to similar to a bar-plot. Until I started doing this revision, I hadnât realized how many data points I had been covering up until I used a geom_point, which when accompanied with a jitter gives a very good picture of the total purchases in those regions over the duration of the data. in all, I need to get better as accompanying data types with the appropriate plots.
